class Solution {
public:

    string reverseWords(string s) {

        vector<string> words;

string temp = " ";

for(int i =0; i<s.lenth(); i++){
if(s[i] != ""){
temp += s[i];
}

else{                //we push all temp words to an vector words 
if(temp != ""){
word.push_back(temp);
temp="";
}
}
}
//last word
if(temp != ""){
 words.push_back(temp);
 }

string ans = ""; //store the reverse

for(int i = words.size()-1; i>=0; i--) //traverse backward from words
ans+=word[i];
if(i != 0){
                ans += " ";
            }
        }

        return ans;
    }
};


Step 1: String → temp

We traverse the string character by character.

Step 2: temp → words

We store:

words.push_back(temp);

Now:

words = {"welcome"}

Why not directly put into ans?

Because while reading the string from left to right, we don't yet know the final reversed order.

At the moment we read:

welcome

we don't know that it must appear at the end of:

"jungle the to welcome"

So we first collect all words:

words = {"welcome", "to", "the", "jungle"}

Then later traverse backwards:

jungle
the
to
welcome

to build:

ans
